         <abstract id="aspace_48e5b018fc95aa08fab1f32b1cf0a9ed">The Havelock Ellis papers contain correspondence and manuscripts on literary and psychological subjects, particularly on the topic of human sexuality. Important correspondents are Sigmund Freud, Bertrand Russell, Herbert Spencer, Thomas Hardy, Leo Tolstoy, Amy Lowell, Louisa Sarah Bevington Guggenberger, Rockwell Kent, Upton Sinclair, Maria Gordon, Marcel Jouhandeau, William Morris, Marc-Andre Raffalovich, Francoise Roussel Delisle (Francois Lafitte-Cyon Delisle), and Rebecca West. The bulk of the papers consists of manuscripts by Ellis, of which the longest is "My Confessions". This work is made up of seventy short pieces, each based upon a problem posed to Ellis by a correspondent. The literary essays are on Thomas Hardy's Jude the Obscure, Marcel Jouhandeau and William Morris.

The addition to this collection contains correspondence and writings primarily from Ellis to his biographer, Houston Peterson. The writings are published and unpublished works written by or about Ellis used in Peterson's biography, including a copy of one of Peterson's lectures on Ellis.</abstract>
