      <bioghist id="aspace_0b884890e368f0fa10bca75555e39ebe">
         <head>Biographical / Historical</head>
         <p>Havelock Ellis (1859-1939) was a British essayist, editor, physician, and psychologist. He studied and challenged the prevalent ideas of human sexual behavior beginning with his research for Man and Women (1894) that led to his major work, the seven volume, Studies in the Psychology of Sex (1897-1928). His last writings were essays on literature and art reprinted in Views and Reviews (1932) and his autobiography <title>
               <part>My Life</part>
            </title> (1939).</p>
      </bioghist>
      <scopecontent id="aspace_27fff75079ab07adbf2e40139edfca48">
         <head>Scope and Contents</head>
         <p>The collection consists of correspondence and manuscripts of Havelock Ellis. Ellis, 1859-1939 began his career in the medical profession but soon gave up general practice for literary and scientific work. The more popular researches of the Freudian school have to a considerable extent overshadowed the methods of Ellis, in which more emphasis is laid on biology and less on clinical experience.</p>
         <p>The more interesting correspondents include William James, Francoise Lafitte-Cyon, Sigmund Freud, Bertrand Russell, poet Louisa Sarah Bevington Guggenberger, Herbert Spencer, Thomas Hardy, Leo Tolstoy, Amy Lowell, Rockwell Kent, Upton Sinclair, Maria Gordon, Marcel Jouhandeau, William Morris, Marc-Andre Raffalovich and Rebecca West. Much of the correspondence consists of editorial matters and complimentary notes. Of greatest interest are the Freud letters. The collection will be of interest to the scholar interested in Ellis and in his relationship to Freud.</p>
         <p>The bulk of the collection is composed of manuscripts by Ellis. Among them is a work entitled My Confessional made up of seventy short pieces. Each is based upon a problem posed to Ellis by one of his correspondents so that the author's opinion on a great number of topics is presented. Other manuscripts include: Sex in Contemporary Life, Marcel Jouhandeau, Intro. to James Hinton's Life In Nature (NY 1934), concerning Jude the Obscure, The Problem of Sexual Potency, William Morris.</p>
         <p>There is also a manuscript, by Sir T. Percy Nunn entitled <title>
               <part>Edudation as a Biological Experiment</part>
            </title>.</p>
      </scopecontent>
