            <scopecontent id="aspace_1c1feac615937a780f43cc452657e6c2">
               <head>Scope and Contents</head>
               <p>The bulk of this addition are letters from Havelock Ellis to his biographer, Houston Peterson, who began working on an essay about Ellis in 1923 that turned into his dissertation at Columbia University. This essay was the foundation of Ellis' biography published in 1928, <title>
                     <part>Havelock Ellis Philosopher of Love</part>
                  </title>. At the time Ellis was known in the medical field for <title>
                     <part>Sexual Inversion</part>
                  </title>, the first volume of what later became his seven-volume work, <title>
                     <part>Studies in the Psychology of Sex</part>
                  </title>, in which he defined his ideas of sexual and gender non-conformity. Ellis was equally known for his writings in literary criticism and feminism of the early 20th century. The rest of the addition is comprised of Ellis's writings from an early age on the literature he exposed himself to and critiqued, as well as his publications in magazines and journals, especially relating to women's reproductive rights and early eugenics.</p>
               <p>Dr. Houston Peterson (1897-1981) began his teaching career at Columbia University, while pursuing a doctorate degree completed in 1929. Peterson taught at Columbia until 1939, while also teaching at Rutgers University from 1929 until his retirement in 1963. Throughout his career he gave lectures on Ellis and many philosophical and literary topics at Columbia's Institute for Arts and Sciences, the Cooper Union where he was the chair of the Social Philosophy division, and throughout the United States.</p>
            </scopecontent>
            <arrangement id="aspace_20938ca67dd2a3913c7f71514fe21cb3">
               <head>Arrangement</head>
               <p>The addition is organized into two sub-series: Havelock Ellis Correspondence and Writings (1925-1931),and  Houston Peterson Papers (1874-1954).</p>
            </arrangement>
